        <p>
            <m>{\color{green} \text{To compare rates,}}</m>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>{\color{green} \text{Express each ratio as a fraction.}}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>{\color{green} \text{Write the equivalenta form for each fraction such that the fraction have the same denominator.}}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>

        <activity>
            <p>
                <em><term>Work in Groups</term></em>
            </p>

            <p>
                Consider the ratios <m>3:4</m> and <m>5:7</m>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Write the two ratios as fractions.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Express each fraction as equivalent fraction such that they have the same denominator.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Identify the greater and lesser fraction.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Discuss and share other groups.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </activity>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Compare the rates <m>3:5</m> and <m>7:8.</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    First we convert the ratios to fractions
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>3:5 =  \amp \frac{3}{5} </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>7:8 = \amp \frac{7}{8} </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Then we find the LCM of the fractions using the denominators.
                </p>
                <p>
                    The LCM of <m>5</m> and <m>8</m> is <m>40.</m>
                    Now to solve for the initial fraction, we multiply one fraction with the value of the denominator of the other fraction.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\frac{3}{5} = \amp \frac{3 \times 8}{5 \times 8} </mrow>
                    </md>, 
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\frac{7}{8} = \amp \frac{7 \times 5}{8 \times 5} </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> = \amp \frac{24}{40}, \frac{35}{40} </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Thus, 
                    <md>
                        <mrow> 3:5 = \amp 24:40</mrow>
                    </md>
                    and
                    <md>
                        <mrow>3:5 = \amp 35:40</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore, <m>3:5</m> is less than <m>7:8</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-comparing-three-ratios-in-different-situations">
        <title>Comparing Three Ratios in Different Situations</title>

        <activity>
            <title>Work in Groups</title>
            <p>
                Consider three ratios 
                <md>
                    <mrow> 3:4, 5:8, 7:12 </mrow>
                </md>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Write the three ratios as fractions.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Express each fractions as an equivalent fraction such that they have a common denominator.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Compare the numerator of the equivalent fractions.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Disucss and share with other groups.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            
        </activity>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Compare and find the greatest ratio among the following:
                    <me>
                        2:3, 5:6, 4:9
                    </me>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Convert the ratios to fractions first.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>2:3 = \amp \frac{2}{3} </mrow>
                    </md>,
                    <md>
                        <mrow>5:6 = \amp \frac{5}{6} </mrow>
                    </md>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>4:9 = \amp \frac{4}{9} </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Then, find the LCM of the fraction which we use the denominators
                </p>
                <p>
                    The LCM of <m>3, 6, 9</m> is <m>18.</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\frac{2}{3} = \amp \frac{2 \times 6}{3 \times 6} </mrow>
                        <mrow>\frac{5}{6} = \amp \frac{5 \times 3}{6 \times 3} </mrow>
                        <mrow>\frac{4}{9} = \amp \frac{4 \times 2}{9 \times 2} </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>= \amp \frac{12}{18}, \frac{15}{18}, \frac{8}{18} </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    This means that;
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>2:3 = \amp 12:18 </mrow>
                        <mrow>5:6 = \amp 15:18 </mrow>
                        <mrow>4:9 = \amp 8:18 </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore, <m>5:6</m> is the greatest ratio.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        
    </subsubsection>

